snippet.textDisplay:
(CAUTION:Long boring post) A few years ago I was watching a vid covering a tech show, kinda like a car show I guess. These young folks were showing off their invention: flexible video screen. My first thot was a military use for "cloak of invisibility" but this is probably the same product. Wonder how bad the inventors got screwed? Motorola probly just showed the vid to their tech team and said "build this". I see many applications for this like clothing, wrap for automobiles and military equipment. This was not the best use for it. I'm old so I like my Startac phones and seems like a tiny split at the hinge point would be ok to live with but then again I mainly use my phone as a phone. Couda cost $300 instead of $1500.
No phone maker will ever do it but how bout a phone for us law enforcement, military and other first responders that just makes calls, texts and maybe a camera. Spend the leftover funds on the the waterproof/tough part. Go back to the old flip phone size so it fits on our gear and can brace it on our shoulder to talk. Oh yeah, have it make that Star Trek sound when it opens. One option: the self defense laser strong enough to incinerate the crotch of the would be rapist. $299.99. Yeah, dreaming. My last StarTac lasted thru missions in 5 countries from jungle to desert to minus 30 degrees. Was under water for almost an hour. Everybody gave me their old phones and accessories but when I called Version that's when everything had to be digital. Damnit. Or I would still be usin them. One even stopped a bullet on a pouch on my body armor. Destroyed the phone but bullet didn't make it to my armor. Could it have saved my life? Maybe. No body armor is bullet "proof", it's bullet "resistant". Hey, I have enough phones to make a vest so maybe I'll build one just to test the theory. Somebody does to build a kevlar or stronger phone case and one for my $700 ballistic prescription sunglasses. THAT would be a winner. L8r.
